COMMODITY:
WHEAT

Triticum spp.:

common (T. aestivum)

durum (T. durum)

spelt (T. spelta)
DEFINITIONS, COVERAGE, REMARKS:
Common and durum wheat are the main types. Among common wheat, the
main varieties are spring and winter, hard and soft, and red and
white. At the national level, different varieties should be reported
separately, reflecting their different uses. Used mainly for human
food.

Defined broadly to include meal, groats and pellets. Strong flours
from hard wheat are used for bread, while durum wheat flour is
used primarily for pasta. Weaker flours from soft wheat are mainly
used in cakes, pastries, biscuits and certain noodles.
See Chapter 11.

Defined broadly to include sharps and other residue from the milling,
sifting or other working of the grain. Contains a little flour.

Pasta made from semolina, or flour, that is mixed with water and
kneaded into a dough. Other ingredients may be included as well. The
dough is then shaped into various forms. This heading is limited to
macaroni that is not cooked, stuffed or otherwise prepared.

The seed embryo. Whole or rolled germ is used for oil extraction by
solvents. Flaked or ground germ is used in bakers' wares, dietetic
preparations, feed supplements and in pharmaceutical preparations.

A baked product of flour or meal of cereals, especially wheat.
Includes ordinary, unleavened, crackers, rusks, etc.

Whole wheat grains that are boiled, dried and cracked, either between
stones or in a hand mill. Very popular in the Near East.

All baked products excluding those listed under bread. Pastry products
may contain ingredients other than wheat flour, such as milk, eggs,
sugar, honey, starch, fats, fruit, seeds, etc.

Starch is the carbohydrate component in many plant cells. A white,
odourless powder that is insoluble in cold water, it forms a paste in
hot water. Wheat starch is used for human consumption and animal feed,
and is processed into glucose and dextrine for industrial use. It is
usually obtained from low-quality flour.

A by-product of the industrial production of starch, wheat gluten is
the preferred cereal gluten for food purposes. Uses include enriching
protein in flours for bread, pasta, etc.

Low-alcohol beverages from fermented flour, e.g. Korean jakju and
takju.
See Chapter 15.

COMMODITY:
RICE PADDY
Oryza spp., mainly oryza sativa
DEFINITIONS, COVERAGE, REMARKS:
Rice grain after threshing and winnowing.Also known as rice in the
husk and rough rice. Used mainly for human food.
Rice grain without hulls or husks. Also known as brown or cargo rice.

White rice milled from imported husked rice. Includes semi-milled,
whole-milled and parboiled rice.

White rice milled from locally grown paddy. Includes semi-milled,
whole-milled and parboiled rice.
Residues from the selection of whole-grain, milled rice.

A by-product of the industrial production of starch. Not suitable for
food use.

See 0023 Rice starch is usually obtained from
broken rice. Use primarily in the photographic industry to prepare "matt" paper.

A by-product of polishing brown rice, comprising the pericarp,
aleurone layer, embryo and some endosperm.
See Chapter 11.
Extracted from bran by pressure or, more frequently, by solvents.
See Chapter 6.
See Chapter 14.
A residue of the extraction of oil. Also known as de-oiled rice bran.
See Chapter 11.

Produced by milling broken or milled rice. Finely ground rice flour is
widely used in infant foods and in noodles.  It is not used in bread
because it lacks the necessary gluten-forming protein.
Low-alcohol beverages, such as rice wine and sake.
See Chapter 15.

Foods prepared by swelling and roasting cereals or cereal products,
e.g. corn flakes, puffed rice; cereals o/t maize, in grain form,
precooked or otherwise prepared.

COMMODITY:
BARLEY
Hordeum spp.: 

two-row barley (H. disticum)

six-row barley

DEFINITIONS, COVERAGE, REMARKS: Whole-seed barley with the husks, hulls and bran removed.

Small, round pellets obtained by the further milling of pot barley.
This definition also includes kibbled, rolled or flaked grains.
See Chapter 11.
A by-product of the production of pot barley.

Fine flour and course meal obtained as milling by-products of pearled
barley.

A grain - usually barley - that has been germinated through a soaking
process and then dried. Malt is used in brewing and distilling, and as
a nutrient additive. Includes whole, ground, flour, and roasted malt,
but excludes extracts and preparations.

A concentrated solution from water-macerated malt, which is used in
infant and dietetic foods and in bread baking.
See Chapter 15.

Beverage that may be alcoholic or non-alcoholic that is made from
fermented malted cereals (mainly barley), water and hops. Non-malted
cereals may also be used. The FAO definition differs from the main
international classifications in that it includes non-alcoholic beer.

COMMODITY:
MAIZE
Zea mays
Corn, Indian corn, mealies
DEFINITIONS, COVERAGE, REMARKS:
A grain with a high germ content. At the national level, hybrid and
ordinary maize should be reported separately owing to widely different
yields and uses. Used largely for animal feed and commercial starch
production.

The seed embryo that is separated during processing and is valued
mainly for its oil.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
A by-product of the milling of shelled maize.
See Chapter 11.
See Chapter 6.
Extracted from germ by pressure or by solvents.
See Chapter 11.
A residue of the extraction of oil from germ.

Maize protein is often called gluten, although it lacks the quality
characteristics of wheat gluten. It is separated from maize during
commercial wet milling and used to enrich animal feeds.

See 0023.
The primary product of the large- scale industrial
wet-milling process. Used mainly for the production of glucose,
dextrin and alcohol.
Prepared either from malted or unmalted cereal.
See Chapter 15.

Although separate data are reported for white maize production owing
to its regional importance, its production is also included in 0056.

A variety of maize that is eaten after the kernels have been heated
and have "popped".

A grain that is tolerant of poor soils, high latitudes and altitudes.
Mainly used in making bread, whisky and beer. When fed to livestock,
it is generally mixed with other grains.

Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets. In northern
countries, rye flour is used primarily in bread.
See Chapter 11.
A milling by-product.

COMMODITY:
OATS
Avena spp., mainly  Avena sativa
DEFINITIONS, COVERAGE, REMARKS:
A plant with open, spreading panicle-bearing large spikelets. Used
primarily in breakfast foods. Makes excellent fodder for horses.

Obtained by crushing or rolling the whole or broken grain; includes
grains flaked, hulled or otherwise worked for human consumption.
See Chapter 11.

By-product of milling oats for human consumption, containing mainly
hulls and fragments of the endosperm (oat millfeed), as well as
residues from hulling, rolling, flaking, etc.

Small-grained cereals that include a large number of different
botanical species. Originated by the domestication of wild African
grasses in the Nile valley and the Sahel zone, millets were
subsequently taken to China and India. These cereals tolerate arid
conditions and possess a small, highly nutritious grain that stores
well. Used locally, both as a food and as a livestock feed. In all
areas where they are cultivated, millets are used in traditional beer
brewing. Also used as a feed for birds.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
See Chapter 11.
A milling by-product.
See Chapter 15.

A traditional beer prepared in African countries in which millets are
cultivated. It is normally consumed while still fermenting.

A cereal that has both food and feed uses. Sorghum is a major food
grain in most of Africa, where it is also used in traditional beer
brewing. It is desirable to report hybrid and other varieties
separately.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
A milling by-product.
See Chapter 11.

A traditional beer prepared in African countries in which sorghum is
cultivated. It is normally consumed while still fermenting.
See Chapter 15.

A minor cereal cultivated primarily in northern regions. Buckwheat is
considered a cereal, although it does not belong to the gramineous
family.

Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets. The flour is
normally used in bread and crackers, and is also mixed with wheat
flour. Meal and groats are normally used for soups.
A milling by-product.
See Chapter 11.

A minor cereal, which tolerates high altitudes, quinoa is cultivated
primarily in Andean countries. Used for food and to make chicha, a
fermented beverage.

COMMODITY:
FONIO
Digitaria spp.:
fonio or findi (D. exilis);
black fonio or hungry rice
(D. iburua)
DEFINITIONS, COVERAGE, REMARKS:
A minor cereal of importance only in West Africa where it is eaten in
place of rice during famines. The seeds are cooked by steaming the
whole grain.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
See Chapter 11.
A milling by-product.

A minor cereal that is a cross between wheat and rye, combining the
quality and yield of wheat with the hardiness of rye.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
See Chapter 11.
A milling by-product.
Minor cereal normally used as bird feed.

A mixture of cereal species that are sown and harvested together.  The
mixture wheat/rye is known as meslin, but in trade is usually
classified with wheat.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
A milling by-product.
See Chapter 11.

Other cereal crops that are not identified separately because of their
minor relevance at the international level. Because of their limited
local importance, some countries report cereals under this commodity
heading that are classified individually by FAO.

Preparations for infant consumption, usually containing some
non-cereal ingredients.

Communion wafers, empty cachets for pharmaceutical use and sealing
wafers.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
See Chapter 11.
A milling by-product.

Cereal grains, excluding barley and oats, that are either rolled,
flaked, pearled, sliced or kibbled.
Used in the preparation of bakers' wares.

COMMODITY: Food Preparations of Flour, Meal or Malt Extract
DEFINITIONS, COVERAGE, REMARKS:
Food preparations of flour, meal, starch or malt extracts, that either
do not contain, or contain less than 50%, cocoa powder. Also, food
preparations of milk that either do not contain, or contain less than
10%, cocoa powder.

A seasonal crop grown in temperate zones all over the world, but
primarily in the northern hemisphere.

Produced from tubers that have been peeled, dried and milled. Includes
flour, meal, flakes, granules and pellets.

Peeled potatoes that are either cooked or uncooked, sliced or
unsliced, and then frozen.

A carbohydrate found in many plant cells. A white odourless powder
that is insoluble in cold water, but forms a paste in hot water. Has
wide food and non-food uses.
The residue and waste from the preparation of potatoes.
See Chapter 11.

A product obtained by heating potato starch mixed with water. Tapioca
may be in the form of flakes, grains, pearls, siftings, seeds or other
similar forms. Used in the preparation of soups and puddings or in
foods for invalids.

A seasonal crop grown in tropical and subtropical regions. Used mainly
for human food. Trade data cover fresh and dried tubers, whether or
not sliced or in the form or pellets.

A semi-permanent crop grown in tropical and subtropical regions.
Sometimes bitter and sweet cassavas are referred to as separate
species, the former being M. esculenta and the latter M. palmata, but
this is incorrect since the toxicity varies according to location.
Cassava is the staple food in many tropical countries. It is not
traded internationally in its fresh state because tubers deteriorate
very rapidly.

A product of tubers that have been peeled, dried and milled; mainly
for human consumption. Includes flour, meal and flakes.

See 0121.
Obtained from cassava starch and used in the preparation of
puddings and in infant foods.

Includes peeled, sliced and sun-dried (cassava chips), as well as
ground and compressed cassava (pellets). Used mainly as livestock
feed.

See 0119.
The principal industrial outlet for cassava. Cassava starch
is used in the foodstuffs, textile and paper industries for the
manufacture of plywood and veneer, adhesives, glucose and dextrine.

Several plants are included in this group, some with edible tubers and
others with edible stems (also called aroids). Yautia is grown mainly
in the Caribbean and is used for food. Trade data cover both fresh and
dried yautia.

COMMODITY:
TARO (COCOYAM)
Dasheen, eddoe, taro, old cocoyam(Colocasia esculenta)
DEFINITIONS, COVERAGE, REMARKS:
Aroids cultivated for their edible starchy corms or underground stems.
Taro is grown throughout the tropics for food. Trade data cover both
fresh and dried taro.

The principal edible yams are widely grown throughout the tropics. A
starchy staple foodstuff, normally eaten as a vegetable, boiled, baked
or fried. In West Africa they are consumed mainly as "fufu", a stiff
glutinous dough. Trade data cover both fresh and dried yams.

Other tubers, roots or rhizomes, fresh, that are not identified
separately because of their minor relevance at the international
level. Because of their limited local importance, some countries
report roots and tubers under this commodity heading that are
classified individually by FAO.

COMMODITY: Flour of Roots and Tubers nes
DEFINITIONS, COVERAGE, REMARKS:
Flour and meal produced from roots and tubers o/t potatoes and
cassava.
Other tubers, roots or rizhomes, dried, o/t potatoes and cassava.

Or levulose, monosaccharide, present with glucose in sweet fruits and
honey.

Produced industrially from starch by hydrolysis with malt diastase.
Used in the brewing industry.
See Chapter 3.

In some producing countries, marginal quantities of sugar cane are
consumed, either directly as food or in the form of juice.

COMMODITY:
SUGAR BEET
Beta vulgaris var. altissima
DEFINITIONS, COVERAGE, REMARKS:
In some producing countries, marginal quantities are consumed, either
directly as food or in the preparation of jams.

A non-refined, crystallized material derived from the juices of
sugar-cane stalk and consisting either wholly or essentially of
sucrose.

A non-refined, crystallized material derived from the juices of
sugar-cane stalk and consisting either wholly or essentially of
sucrose.

A non-refined, crystallized material derived from the juices extracted
from the root of the sugar beet and consisting either wholly or
essentially of sucrose.

A non-refined, crystallized material derived from the juices extracted
from the root of the sugar beet and consisting either wholly or
essentially of sucrose.

Maple syrup is produced by atmospheric boiling of maple sap in an
open-pan evaporator. Continuing the evaporation process until the
syrup crystalizes yields maple sugar.

Includes minor sugar crops of local importance. In the case of saps,
production is to be expressed in liquid equivalent.

The sum of codes 0158 and 0159.
Processed further to obtain refined sugar.

The sum of codes 0158 and 0159. Processed further to obtain refined
sugar.

Generally derived from sugar cane through traditional methods without
centrifugation.

Generally derived from sugar cane through traditional methods without
centrifugation.

Production covers domestic production, plus or minus imports and/or
exports of raw centrifugal sugar in terms of refined sugar.

Production covers domestic production, plus or minus imports and/or
exports of raw centrifugal sugar in terms of refined sugar.

A by-product of the extraction or refining of beet or cane sugar or of
the production of fructose from maize. Used for feed, food, industrial
alcohol, alcoholic beverages and ethanol.

A by-product of the extraction or refining of beet or cane sugar or of
the production of fructose from maize. Used for feed, food, industrial
alcohol, alcoholic beverages and ethanol.

Monosaccharide found in fruits and honey, commercially produced from
glucose, sucrose or by hydrolysis of inulin (polysaccharide found
mainly in the tubers of the dahlia and the Jerusalem artichoke).
Especially suitable for use by diabetics.
See Chapter 3.

Includes invert sugar, caramel, golden syrup, artificial honey,
maltose other than chemically pure, sorghum and palm sugars. See also
the general note in the introduction.

Sugar confectionery, including chewing gum, that does not contain
cocoa. Includes white chocolate.
See Chapter 11.
See Chapter 11.

Residue from the extraction of sugar from the root of sugar beets.
Used for animal feed.
See Chapter 11.
See Chapter 11.

Residue consisting of the fibrous portion of the sugar cane after the
juice has been extracted. Used as a fuel in sugar mills, as an animal
feed, and in paper production.
See Chapter 3.

Glucose is a monosaccharide produced by hydrolysing starch with acids
and/or enzymes.  Dextrose is chemically pure glucose. Used in the food
industry, in brewing, in tobacco fermentation and in pharmaceutical
products.
Also known as milk sugar. Produced commercially from whey.
See Chapter 3.

High-intensity or low-caloric sweetening agents that are produced
chemically.

Also known as HFCS (high-fructose corn syrup), HFSS (high-fructose
starch syrup), HFGS (high-fructose glucose syrup). Isoglucose is a new
type of starch syrup where glucose has been isomerized to fructose by
using one or more isomerizing enzymes. Most important of the
sweeteners manufactured from maize starch. Widely used in the
production of food and soft drinks.
See Chapter 3.

Only species of Phaseolus should be included, though several countries
also include certain types of beans. Commonly classified as Vigna
(angularis, mungo, radiata, aconitifolia). In the past, these species
were also classified as Phaseolus.

pigeon pea, cajan pea, Congo bean (Cajanus cajan)

Used mainly for animal feed.

Used primarily for feed, though in some parts of Africa and in Latin

Vigna spp. other than those included in 0176 and 0195
Other pulses that are not identified separately because of their minor

DEFINITIONS, COVERAGE, REMARKS: Produced mainly in Europe and Asia.

Produced mainly in Mediterranean countries, the United States and

Produced mainly in Mediterranean countries, the United States and

Produced in temperate zones of the Northern Hemisphere, particularly

KOLA NUTS
kola, cola, Sudan cola nut  (Cola nitida; C. vera; C. acuminata)

Produced mainly in Africa. Kola nuts, containing 2.4 to 2.6% caffeine,

Produced mainly in Mediterranean countries and the United States.

ARECA NUTS
areca, betel nut (Areca catechu)
DEFINITIONS, COVERAGE, REMARKS:
Produced mainly in the Far East. Areca nuts are used mainly as

Around 55% of the weight in shell.
Around 25% of the weight in shell.
Around 55% of the weight in shell.
Around 53% of the weight in shell.
Around 50% of the weight in shell.

Other nuts that are not identified separately because of their minor

Mainly roasted, whether or not containing vegetable oils, salt,
flavours, spices or other additives. Excludes prepared groundnuts,
except when mixed with other nuts.

The most important oil crop. Also widely consumed as a bean and in the
form of various derived products because of its high protein content,
e.g. soya milk, meat, etc.

The most important oil crop. Also widely consumed as a bean and in the
form of various derived products because of its high protein content,
e.g. soya milk, meat, etc.
See Chapter 11.
Obtained by solvent extraction from the beans. Used mainly for food.

Oilcake and other solid residues (except dregs), whether or not
ground, or in the form of pellets, resulting from the extraction of

A fermented soya product from defatted soybeand and wheat or other
cereals that is filtered and pasteurized.

A fermented, salty condiment. Soya paste can be produced through brine
fermentation of low- moisture soya curd.

Obtained by precipitating proteins from soya milk and removing the
fluid. Can be fermented or non-fermented.

For trade data, groundnuts in shell are converted at 70% and reported
on a shelled basis.
Used as direct food and for extracting oil.
See Chapter 11.
Obtained by pressure or solvent extraction. Used mainly for food.
Residue from oil extraction.
Roasted, salted, flavoured, etc.

Obtained by grinding roasted peanuts. In addition to fat, at 40-46%,
peanut butter contains all other components of the nuts.

In shell, covered by the endocarp, while exocarp (the smooth outer
skin) and mesocarp (the fibrous covering) are removed. Immature nuts
contain a milky juice that is consumed as a refreshing drink. Mature
nuts are consumed as such, or processed for copra or desiccated
coconut. The flesh, from which copra/oil is extracted, constitutes
40-70% of the weight of the husked coconut. The oil content is about
36% of the flesh.

Dried, shredded flesh of coconut processed for human consumption. It
retains most of the oil and proteins of the fresh nut and is mainly
used in confectionery and baking.
The dried flesh of coconut from which the oil is extracted.

Obtained by pressure from copra and by solvent from the residues of
pressure extraction. Has both food and industrial uses.
See Chapter 11.
Residue from oil extraction.

The oil palm produces bunches containing a large number of fruits with
the fleshy mesocarp enclosing a kernel that is covered by a very hard
shell. FAO considers palm oil (coming from the pulp) and palm kernels
to be primary products. The oil extraction rate from a bunch varies
from 17 to 27% for palm oil, and from 4 to 10% for palm kernels.

Seeds of the oil palm. Babassu kernels (Orbignya speciosa) are often
reported as palm kernels.
See Chapter 14.

Obtained from the mesocarp of the fruit of the oil palm by pressure,
and also by solvent from the residues of the pressure extraction.

Obtained from the kernel of the nut of the fruits of the oil palm by
pressure in two or three stages at different temperatures. Including
oil of babassu kernels.
Residue from oil extraction.
Includes table olives and olives for oil.
See Chapter 11.

Obtained from olives by mechanical or other physical means. Olive oil
is the only vegetable oil that can be consumed without refining.

Production data refer only to the nut contained in the fruit although
        the pulp around the nut is also edible.

A very important vegetable oil in West Africa. Used as a substitute
for cocoa butter and in cosmetics.

Valued mainly for their oil, which is used in pharmaceutical products.
        Ground seedcakes are used as fertilizers (castor oil pomace).
See Chapter 14.

Obtained by pressure or by solvent. Uses include mainly industrial
ones, in pharmaceuticals and cosmetics.

Valued mainly for its oil. Minor uses include as a human food and as

Obtained by pressure extraction. Mainly for food use.
See Chapter 11.

Residue from oil extraction. The cake is used for feed if it is from

Valued mainly for its oil. Older varieties are rich in Erucic acid,

Obtained by pressure extraction for food use. Oil recovered with

Residue from oil extraction.

Residues make up about 40% of the olives crushed for oil, but account

Oil extracted from olive residues with solvents.

Margarine is made principally from one or more hydrogenated vegetable
or animal fats or oils in which is dispersed an aqueous potion
containing milk products, salt, flavouring agents and other additives.
Shortening is a product similar to margarine, but with a higher animal
fat content. Shortening and compound fats are used primarily for
baking and frying. The fat content of margarine and shortening varies
from 70 to 90%.
